Continuing from the hint, to choose real-valued solutions, we choose
$C_2 = \bar{C_1}$, so that the general solution becomes:

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y} = C_1 \mathbf{y_1} + C_2 \mathbf{y_2} = C_1 \mathbf{y_1} + \overline{C_1 \mathbf{y_1}} = 2 \mathrm{Re}\left[ C_1 \mathbf{y_1} \right]
\end{align*}

Recall that

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y_1} = \mathbf{k_1} \exp{\lambda_1 t} = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2+3i \\ 1 \end{array} \right] \exp{(1+2i)t}
\end{align*}

Since

\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Re} \left[ \mathbf{y_1} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] e^t \cos{2t} + \left[ \begin{array}{c} -3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] e^t \sin{2t}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Im} \left[ \mathbf{y_1} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] e^t \cos{2t} + \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] e^t \sin{2t}
\end{align*}

The general form of real-valued solutions is:

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y} &= D_1 \mathrm{Re} \left[ \mathbf{y_1} \right] + D_2 \mathrm{Im} \left[ \mathbf{y_1} \right] \\
&= D_1 \left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] e^t \cos{2t} + \left[ \begin{array}{c} -3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] e^t \sin{2t} \right)\\
&+ D_2 \left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} 3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] e^t \cos{2t} + \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] e^t \sin{2t} \right)
\end{align*}

where $D_1$ and $D_2$ are real constants.

Their relationship with the previous constants are
$D_1 = 2 \mathrm{Re} \left[ C_1 \right]$ and
$D_2 = -2 \mathrm{Im} \left[ C_1 \right] = e^t$

Now if we impose the initial condition
$\mathbf{y}(0) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \end{array} \right]$, we
get

\begin{align*}
D_1 \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] + D_2 \left[ \begin{array}{c} 3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right]
=  \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \end{array} \right]
\end{align*}

Thus, $D_1 = 0 ~$ and $D_2 = \frac{1}{3}$, and the solution of the
initial value problem is

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{3} \left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} 3 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] e^t \cos{2t} + \left[ \begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] e^t \sin{2t} \right)
= \frac{e^t}{3} \left[ \begin{array}{c} 3 \cos{2t} + 2 \sin{2t} \\ \sin{2t} \end{array} \right]
\end{align*}

Alternatively, one can solve directly from

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y} = 2 \mathrm{Re}\left[ C_1 \mathbf{y_1} \right]
\end{align*}

And impose the initial condition
$\mathbf{y}_0 = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \end{array} \right]$
direcly to find that $C_1 = -\frac{i}{6}$.

Then compute the real part to get the same result as above. The amount
of algebra involved will be slightly less.
